            "generated_answer": "## American Express Operating Margin Analysis\n\n### Why Traditional Operating Margin Is Not the Most Useful Metric for AMEX\n\nOperating margin (Operating Income / Total Revenue) is **not the most useful metric** for American Express, and here's why:\n\nAmerican Express is fundamentally a **financial services / payments network company**, not an industrial or retail company. Its economics are better understood through metrics specific to financial services:\n\n---\n\n### What the Context Tells Us Instead\n\nFrom the provided data, more relevant profitability indicators for AMEX include:\n\n| Metric | 2022 | 2021 | 2020 |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Return on Average Equity** | 32.3% | 33.7% | 14.2% |\n| **Net Interest Yield on Card Member Loans** | 10.6% | 10.7% | 11.5% |\n| **Pretax Income Margin*** | ~18.1% | ~25.2% | ~11.9% |\n| **Net Income** | $7,514M | $8,060M | $3,135M |\n\n*Calculated as Pretax Income / Total Revenues Net of Interest Expense*\n\n---\n\n### Key Reasons Operating Margin Is Inappropriate Here:\n\n1. **Revenue is net of interest expense** \u2014 AMEX reports \"Total revenues **net of interest expense**\" ($52.9B in 2022), which is an industry-standard presentation for financial firms, making gross revenue comparisons misleading.\n\n2. **Provisions for credit losses** are a core operating cost (analogous to cost of goods sold), not a below-the-line item \u2014 these swung dramatically from **+$4.7B (2020)** to **-$1.4B (2021)** to **+$2.2B (2022)**, reflecting credit cycle dynamics rather than operational efficiency.\n\n3. **No traditional \"operating income\" line** is presented in AMEX's income statement \u2014 the financials go directly from revenues to expenses to **pretax income**.\n\n---\n\n### Conclusion\n\nRather than improving operating margin, the data suggests **some pressure on profitability in 2022**: pretax income *declined* from $10.7B to $9.6",
