            "generated_answer": "## Adobe's Operating Margin Analysis (FY2020\u2013FY2022)\n\nBased on the provided financial data, I can calculate Adobe's operating margins for the three most recent fiscal years:\n\n| Fiscal Year | Total Revenue | Operating Income | Operating Margin |\n|-------------|--------------|-----------------|-----------------|\n| FY2020 | $12,868M | $4,237M | **32.9%** |\n| FY2021 | $15,785M | $5,802M | **36.8%** |\n| FY2022 | $17,606M | $6,098M | **34.6%** |\n\n---\n\n### Assessment\n\n**The operating margin profile is mixed, not clearly improving as of FY2022.**\n\n- From FY2020 to FY2021, operating margin **improved significantly** by ~390 basis points (32.9% \u2192 36.8%), demonstrating strong operating leverage.\n- However, from FY2021 to FY2022, operating margin **declined** by ~220 basis points (36.8% \u2192 34.6%), driven by operating expenses growing faster than revenue \u2014 notably **R&D** (+$447M) and **Sales & Marketing** (+$647M).\n\n### Is Operating Margin a Useful Metric Here?\n\n**Yes, operating margin is a highly relevant metric for Adobe.** As a predominantly **subscription-based software company** (subscriptions representing ~93% of FY2022 revenue), Adobe benefits from scalable, recurring revenue with relatively predictable costs, making operating margin a strong indicator of business efficiency and profitability trends.\n\n**Conclusion:** Adobe does **not** show a consistently improving operating margin as of FY2022; the margin retreated from its FY2021 peak due to accelerated investment in operating expenses.",
