            "question": "Does AMD have a reasonably healthy liquidity profile based on its quick ratio for FY22? If the quick ratio is not relevant to measure liquidity, please state that and explain why.",
            "gold_answer": "Yes. The quick ratio is 1.57, calculated as (cash and cash equivalents+Short term investments+Accounts receivable, net+receivables from related parties)/ (current liabilities).",
            "generated_answer": "## AMD Liquidity Analysis: Quick Ratio for FY22\n\n### Calculating the Quick Ratio\n\nThe **Quick Ratio** = (Cash & Cash Equivalents + Short-term Investments + Accounts Receivable) / Current Liabilities\n\nUsing FY22 balance sheet data:\n\n| Component | Amount ($ millions) |\n|---|---|\n| Cash & Cash Equivalents | $4,835 |\n| Short-term Investments | $1,020 |\n| Accounts Receivable, net | $4,126 |\n| **Total Quick Assets** | **$9,981** |\n| Current Liabilities | $6,369 |\n\n$$\\text{Quick Ratio} = \\frac{\\$9,981}{\\$6,369} \\approx \\textbf{1.57x}$$\n\n---\n\n### Assessment\n\n**Yes, AMD demonstrates a reasonably healthy liquidity profile.** A quick ratio of **~1.57x** indicates that AMD has approximately **$1.57 in liquid assets for every $1.00 of current liabilities**, which is comfortably above the general benchmark of 1.0x.\n\nKey supporting observations:\n- **Cash alone ($4,835M)** nearly covers **76% of current liabilities ($6,369M)**\n- The quick ratio **improved significantly** from FY21, where cash was only $2,535M against current liabilities of $4,240M (~0.85x quick ratio), suggesting meaningful liquidity improvement year-over-year\n- Operating activities generated **$3,565M in cash flow** in FY22, further supporting liquidity strength\n\nThe quick ratio is **relevant here** as AMD is a semiconductor company with meaningful inventory ($3,771M) that may not be immediately liquid, making the quick ratio a more conservative and appropriate measure than the current ratio.",
