            "question": "Does AMEX have an improving operating margin profile as of 2022? If operating margin is not a useful metric for a company like this, then state that and explain why.",
            "gold_answer": "Performance is not measured through operating margin",
            "generated_answer": "## Operating Margin Analysis for American Express (AMEX)\n\n### Why Traditional Operating Margin Is Not the Most Useful Metric Here\n\nOperating margin (Operating Income / Revenue) is **not the most meaningful metric** for a financial services company like American Express. Here's why:\n\n1. **Revenue Definition is Ambiguous**: AMEX's \"revenue\" is reported as **\"Total revenues net of interest expense\"** \u2014 meaning interest expense is already netted out before arriving at the top-line figure. This is standard for financial firms but makes the numerator and denominator difficult to compare to industrial companies.\n\n2. **Provisions for Credit Losses are a Core Operating Cost**: For a lending/payments business, credit loss provisions are not a peripheral item \u2014 they are central to the business model. Whether to include or exclude them from an \"operating\" calculation significantly changes the picture.\n\n---\n\n### More Relevant Profitability Metrics from the Context\n\nUsing **Pretax Income Margin** (Pretax Income / Total Revenues Net of Interest Expense):\n\n| Year | Pretax Income | Total Revenues Net of Int. Exp. | Pretax Margin |\n|------|--------------|----------------------------------|---------------|\n| 2020 | $4,296M | $36,087M | **11.9%** |\n| 2021 | $10,689M | $42,380M | **25.2%** |\n| 2022 | $9,585M | $52,862M | **18.1%** |\n\n### Observations:\n\n- The pretax margin **declined from 2021 to 2022**, primarily due to a **swing in provisions for credit losses** (from a benefit of -$1,419M in 2021 to a charge of +$2,182M in 2022) and rising expenses (+$7,985M increase).\n- However, revenues grew strongly (+25% in 2022), and the 2021 margin was artificially elevated by **reserve releases** (negative provisions).\n- **Return on average equity** also declined slightly: 33.7% (2021) \u2192 32.3% (2022), though it remains very strong.\n\n### Conclusion\n\n> **Operating margin is not the ideal metric for AMEX** given its nature",
