            "question": "Does AMEX have an improving operating margin profile as of 2022? If operating margin is not a useful metric for a company like this, then state that and explain why.",
            "gold_answer": "Performance is not measured through operating margin",
            "generated_answer": "## AMEX Operating Margin Analysis\n\n### Why Traditional Operating Margin Is Not the Most Useful Metric for AMEX\n\nOperating margin (Operating Income / Total Revenues) is **not the most meaningful metric** for American Express. Here's why:\n\nAmerican Express is a **financial services company**, not an industrial or retail business. Its economics are fundamentally different:\n\n- **Revenue is reported \"net of interest expense\"** \u2014 interest expense is deducted from revenues rather than treated as an operating cost, which is standard practice for financial firms. This makes the revenue base itself structurally different from non-financial companies.\n- **Provisions for credit losses** function similarly to a cost of goods sold \u2014 they are a core, recurring cost of the lending business, not a one-time item.\n- The company does not report a separate \"operating income\" line; profitability is better assessed through **pretax income, net income, return on equity, and net interest yield**.\n\n---\n\n### More Relevant Profitability Indicators (from the data)\n\n| Metric | 2022 | 2021 | 2020 |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Total Revenues Net of Interest Expense | $52,862M | $42,380M | $36,087M |\n| Pretax Income | $9,585M | $10,689M | $4,296M |\n| Net Income | $7,514M | $8,060M | $3,135M |\n| Pretax Margin (Pretax / Net Revenue) | **18.1%** | **25.2%** | **11.9%** |\n| Return on Average Equity | **32.3%** | **33.7%** | **14.2%** |\n\n### Interpretation\n\n- While profitability **improved dramatically from 2020 to 2021**, the pretax margin **declined from 25.2% to 18.1% in 2022**, driven by:\n  - A **swing in provisions for credit losses** from a benefit of $(1,419)M in 2021 to a charge of $2,182M in 2022 (a $3.6B headwind)\n  - **Expenses growing 24%** ($41,095M vs",
