            "generated_answer": "## AMD Liquidity Analysis: Quick Ratio for FY2022\n\n### Calculating the Quick Ratio\n\nThe **Quick Ratio** = (Cash + Short-term Investments + Accounts Receivable) / Current Liabilities\n\nUsing FY2022 Balance Sheet data:\n\n| Component | Amount ($ millions) |\n|---|---|\n| Cash and Cash Equivalents | $4,835 |\n| Short-term Investments | $1,020 |\n| Accounts Receivable, net | $4,126 |\n| **Total Quick Assets** | **$9,981** |\n| **Current Liabilities** | **$6,369** |\n\n$$\\text{Quick Ratio} = \\frac{\\$9,981}{\\$6,369} = \\approx \\textbf{1.57x}$$\n\n---\n\n### Assessment\n\n**Yes, AMD demonstrates a reasonably healthy liquidity profile.** A quick ratio of **1.57x** indicates that:\n\n- AMD has **$1.57 in liquid assets for every $1.00 of current liabilities**, comfortably above the general benchmark of **1.0x**\n- The company can meet its short-term obligations **without relying on inventory liquidation**\n- Cash and equivalents alone ($4,835M) nearly cover **76% of current liabilities** ($6,369M)\n\n### Conclusion\nThe quick ratio is **relevant and appropriate** for AMD as a fabless semiconductor company, and the result reflects a **solid near-term liquidity position** as of FY2022.",
